---
// About — a single, dead-end chapter. Its paper isn't top-inset via StageLeft
// (StageLeft vertically centers within one viewport, which only makes sense
// for content that fits in one) — it's anchored near the top instead, since
// motion.ts scrubs its own y continuously as the user scrolls to reveal
// content taller than the viewport. See docs/epics/epic-17-*.
import Chapter from "@components/Chapter.astro";
---

<div class="absolute left-(--stage-left-inset) top-32">
  <Chapter id="about">
    <div slot="main" class="max-w-3xl pt-16">
      <h2 class="text-2xl mb-10 pb-2 italic border-b border-sage">About</h2>
      <p class="text-2xl mb-4">
        I'm a designer and developer working out of a small studio in the
        Durango area, building websites and digital tools for a select group of
        clients who care about the details as much as I do.
      </p>
      <p class="text-2xl mb-4">
        My background is split evenly between design and engineering, which
        means I spend as much time thinking about how something should feel as I
        do making sure it actually works. A site that looks considered but loads
        slowly, or one that's fast but forgettable, both miss the point.
      </p>
      <p class="text-2xl mb-4">
        Before Bakehouse, I spent a decade building interaction design and
        front-end systems for small product studios and non-profits — mostly the
        kind of work where you wear every hat at once, which turned out to be
        good training for running a studio of one.
      </p>
      <p class="text-2xl mb-4">
        These days the projects are smaller and more deliberate. I like working
        directly with the people who'll use what I build, rather than through
        layers of process, and I like projects with a clear point of view — a
        restaurant, a maker, a small practice — more than anything that needs to
        be all things to all people.
      </p>
      <p class="text-2xl mb-4">
        Typography and pacing matter to me as much as color and layout. I'd
        rather a page say less, and say it well, than fill every inch of the
        screen. That restraint is really the whole design philosophy behind this
        site, and behind the ones I build for other people.
      </p>
      <p class="text-2xl mb-4">
        When I'm not at the keyboard I'm usually outside — this part of Colorado
        makes that easy — and most of what ends up on a client's site is
        inspired by paying attention to how things are actually made: paper,
        wood, bread, the occasional bakehouse.
      </p>
      <p class="text-2xl mb-4">
        If any of this sounds like your kind of project, <a
          href="#"
          class="link">reach out</a
        > — I'd like to hear about it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </Chapter>
</div>

<style>
  /*
   * Same custom underline treatment as the intro chapter's .link — kept
   * local rather than shared since Content.astro files intentionally don't
   * depend on one another (see docs/architecture.md, "two decoupled parts").
   * background-image/size/position and text-shadow have no Tailwind
   * equivalent (CLAUDE.md reason 1).
   */
  .link {
    --link-color: var(--color-link-intro);
    --paper-bg: var(--color-foreground);
    --underline-color: color-mix(
      in srgb,
      var(--color-link-intro) 65%,
      transparent
    );

    color: var(--link-color);
    font-weight: 600;
    text-decoration: none;

    background-image: linear-gradient(
      var(--underline-color),
      var(--underline-color)
    );
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
    background-size: 88% 0.5px;
    background-position: 55% 1.15em;

    text-shadow:
      0.035em 0 var(--paper-bg),
      -0.035em 0 var(--paper-bg),
      0.07em 0 var(--paper-bg),
      -0.07em 0 var(--paper-bg);
  }
</style>
